948
01:06:21,645 --> 01:06:25,774
-Holiday cheer.
-Jerry, you're reaching.

949
01:06:29,444 --> 01:06:31,071
"You're reaching."

950
01:06:33,574 --> 01:06:39,037
All the stomach medicine up there.
I love that. Like, "Oh, I'm..."

951
01:06:39,329 --> 01:06:42,457
-I never noticed.
-It's what they go through.

952
01:06:42,833 --> 01:06:45,836
Acute observations.
I love this shot.

953
01:06:46,420 --> 01:06:48,922
-Him in his underwear?
-Yes.

954
01:06:51,592 --> 01:06:53,093
It's just too easy.

955
01:06:53,302 --> 01:06:57,598
For two days we stood around,
a bunch of naked people.

956
01:06:57,973 --> 01:07:02,477
-You loved every second.
-Not all of it. Brothers were swinging.

957
01:07:03,103 --> 01:07:04,938
How can I keep up?

958
01:07:07,232 --> 01:07:09,943
I like this shot too, by the way.

959
01:07:10,110 --> 01:07:14,781
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.
-I'm telling you, it was a good job.

960
01:07:17,993 --> 01:07:21,955
Some dudes might have coin,
but they'll never have kwan.

961
01:07:22,164 --> 01:07:23,290
What is--?

962
01:07:23,498 --> 01:07:28,921
It means love, respect, community
and dollars. The entire package.

963
01:07:31,131 --> 01:07:32,132
The kwan.

964
01:07:32,841 --> 01:07:36,261
I love, Cuba,
when you experience kwan.

965
01:07:36,470 --> 01:07:37,846
I love that.

966
01:07:38,805 --> 01:07:42,309
It's like he's listening
to some good music.

967
01:07:42,517 --> 01:07:44,978
It's the feeling of kwan.

968
01:07:47,648 --> 01:07:51,401
But those players you mentioned
are marquee players.

969
01:07:53,946 --> 01:07:57,366
How can he use the "M" word
in that way?

970
01:08:02,037 --> 01:08:05,207
This is a scene we auditioned with.
Am I right?

971
01:08:05,457 --> 01:08:06,917
Yeah.

972
01:08:09,169 --> 01:08:11,213
"Telling me to dance."

973
01:08:14,091 --> 01:08:18,053
...10 get back to the guy
who first started playing.

974
01:08:18,262 --> 01:08:23,183
Way back when you were a kid, it
wasn't just about the money, was it?

975
01:08:24,059 --> 01:08:25,477
Was it?

976
01:08:26,603 --> 01:08:27,729
Was it?

977
01:08:29,898 --> 01:08:33,443
Do your job.
Don't you tell me to dance!

978
01:08:35,237 --> 01:08:39,533
When you kicked the wall, I laughed.
You went crazy.

979
01:08:40,284 --> 01:08:45,706
I do not dance, and I do not start
pre-season without a contract!

980
01:08:46,581 --> 01:08:50,294
Another real Tom moment.
Tom missing the goal.

981
01:08:51,044 --> 01:08:56,425
The hug you gave him Saturday.
Nothing half-assed.

982
01:08:59,553 --> 01:09:02,639
You don't know
what it's like to be me.

983
01:09:05,100 --> 01:09:06,893
I wanted to have...

984
01:09:07,102 --> 01:09:10,188
...Makeup put cuts on me
to show I was tough.

985
01:09:10,439 --> 01:09:15,027
But it almost didn't show.
I was so wet, everything drained down.

986
01:09:15,235 --> 01:09:18,113
The blood and all, because
he took a beating.

987
01:09:22,451 --> 01:09:25,287
I love this. I love this.

988
01:09:25,454 --> 01:09:28,915
-Classic.
-"Help me help you."

989
01:09:29,082 --> 01:09:33,337
And the audience wants to laugh here,
and you let them!

990
01:09:34,921 --> 01:09:40,135
I mean, this could've been
the other thing altogether.

991
01:09:40,344 --> 01:09:43,805
Genuine, beautiful,
vulnerable, angry.

992
01:09:44,056 --> 01:09:49,227
And he laughed in your face!
It is genius!

993
01:09:52,064 --> 01:09:54,941
Yeah! Oh, that's great.

994
01:09:57,152 --> 01:10:01,823
Oh, you guys. God. God!

995
01:10:04,326 --> 01:10:08,080
-Do that again.
- I thought you were gonna go frontal.

996
01:10:08,246 --> 01:10:10,832
Well, we have that footage, Cuba.

997
01:10:11,833 --> 01:10:16,838
-Okay, this is where I leave!
-Director's cut.

998
01:10:17,005 --> 01:10:21,093
Join me on chapter five or seven.

999
01:10:21,760 --> 01:10:23,762
You mean five and seven?

1000
01:10:23,970 --> 01:10:27,766
Five and seven, and 15 as well.

1001
01:10:27,974 --> 01:10:32,729
You spent a lot of time thinking
about all the airports...

1002
01:10:32,938 --> 01:10:35,982
...the travelling, the different...

1003
01:10:36,149 --> 01:10:40,028
...hours with Janusz discussing it
and music...

1004
01:10:40,195 --> 01:10:44,324
People passing through
from capsule to capsule.

1005
01:10:44,866 --> 01:10:50,205
Living their life. And that was
our plan for the airport scenes.

1006
01:10:51,123 --> 01:10:54,876
This is the day James L. Brooks
was laughing so hard.

1007
01:10:55,043 --> 01:10:58,130
You were like, "Quiet!"
He was like:

1008
01:11:01,800 --> 01:11:05,470
I love that scene with you guys
in the bathroom.

1009
01:11:05,804 --> 01:11:07,389
I couldn't wait to play it.

1010
01:11:07,806 --> 01:11:11,101
You gotta do that again.
I wanna watch it.

1011
01:11:12,811 --> 01:11:14,896
Stop the tape!

1012
01:11:15,063 --> 01:11:18,400
You know, the other night,
I was lonely.

1013
01:11:18,608 --> 01:11:20,944
I felt you understood something.

1014
01:11:21,945 --> 01:11:24,781
We've got a company to think about.

1015
01:11:24,990 --> 01:11:28,034
I'll never take advantage
of you again.

1016
01:11:28,910 --> 01:11:32,330
-Didn't Suzanne Somers live next door?
-Did she?

1017
01:11:32,539 --> 01:11:36,334
That's right, you were in Venice!
Is that where--7?

1018
01:11:36,501 --> 01:11:39,921
-Manhattan Beach.
-Manhattan Beach, right.

1019
01:11:41,548 --> 01:11:44,676
Think about what's wrong
and how to fix it.

1020
01:11:44,926 --> 01:11:47,554
And, you know, just be alone.

1021
01:11:48,138 --> 01:11:49,890
Alone.

1022
01:11:50,515 --> 01:11:53,393
-Alone, alone, alone.
-Alone, alone.

1023
01:11:55,896 --> 01:11:59,524
-You wanna go out to dinner?
-I know a great place.

1024
01:12:00,108 --> 01:12:02,569
I love this band, they were great.

1025
01:12:04,446 --> 01:12:08,825
-What do you mean by stalking?
-Coming over uninvited.

1026
01:12:09,326 --> 01:12:14,039
"Coming over uninvited"? So Romeo
on your balcony is a stalker?

1027
01:12:16,291 --> 01:12:18,460
How many days did you shoot this?

1028
01:12:18,877 --> 01:12:21,379
Boy, I think four days.

1029
01:12:22,214 --> 01:12:25,300
Him walking into it.
It's like, "Help me."

1030
01:12:25,467 --> 01:12:28,803
We did some takes where Tom
just came in.

1031
01:12:29,054 --> 01:12:30,138
Unannounced.

1032
01:12:30,347 --> 01:12:34,100
It was your first moment
right there, isn't it?

1033
01:12:34,309 --> 01:12:36,186
With the women's groups.

1034
01:12:36,394 --> 01:12:38,313
They'd never met you.

1035
01:12:38,897 --> 01:12:41,066
-They hadn't met him?
-No.

1036
01:12:41,233 --> 01:12:44,569
They didn't say he'd be there,
and he walked in.

1037
01:12:44,903 --> 01:12:48,073
-He just walked in.
-Did you use any of it?

1038
01:12:48,240 --> 01:12:50,909
Yeah, that front angle was one.

1039
01:12:51,117 --> 01:12:54,246
Todd Louiso,
who plays Chad the Nanny.

1040
01:12:54,412 --> 01:12:56,414
-He's genius.
-He's genius...

1041
01:12:56,831 --> 01:12:59,251
...and so is Renee, listening.

1042
01:12:59,417 --> 01:13:02,504
I love this shot of Renee listening.

1043
01:13:03,505 --> 01:13:07,467
-Look at that.
-Yeah, my goodness, she looks great.

1044
01:13:09,010 --> 01:13:11,763
We tell the audience
how we feel about--

1045
01:13:11,972 --> 01:13:14,849
-About every single scene.
-Hey!

1046
01:13:16,059 --> 01:13:21,898
-Okay, there's something that...
-Look at that, against the wall.

1047
01:13:24,234 --> 01:13:27,362
-Love how Bonnie take this away.
-She goes:

1048
01:13:27,529 --> 01:13:29,864
"For me? Wow!"

1049
01:13:31,116 --> 01:13:32,534
Yes, he's so--

1050
01:13:34,869 --> 01:13:36,329
"This is an energy bar."

1051
01:13:37,289 --> 01:13:41,376
That's more than a dress,
that's an Audrey Hepburn movie.

1052
01:13:41,876 --> 01:13:46,339
That was an interesting dress.
That dress has a story.

1053
01:13:46,548 --> 01:13:50,010
-That dress had some straps.
-Yes, it has straps.

1054
01:13:50,218 --> 01:13:52,887
-Breakaway straps.
-Breakaway straps.

1055
01:13:54,097 --> 01:13:58,852
They would not reliably
break away, however.

1056
01:14:00,353 --> 01:14:02,397
-They came off easily.
-Sometimes.

1057
01:14:02,897 --> 01:14:04,983
When they weren't supposed to.

1058
01:14:05,150 --> 01:14:08,236
Sometimes they didn't
when they should.

1059
01:14:08,570 --> 01:14:10,488
I love that look.

1060
01:14:11,072 --> 01:14:15,160
Let me embarrass you for a moment
here, okay?

1061
01:14:15,368 --> 01:14:18,580
This scene is where I felt...

1062
01:14:18,997 --> 01:14:22,334
...really that I wanted to direct.

1063
01:14:22,917 --> 01:14:27,589
It gave you a chance to do more
than just write and capture stuff.

1064
01:14:28,006 --> 01:14:31,926
And it's Tom with Jonathan here.

1065
01:14:32,927 --> 01:14:36,306
And Renee just watching them.

1066
01:14:36,514 --> 01:14:41,102
And I remember watching this
through the camera...

1067
01:14:41,269 --> 01:14:43,480
...particularly this next shot.

1068
01:14:44,939 --> 01:14:49,611
And I went nuts.
I just started jumping around.

1069
01:14:49,944 --> 01:14:53,406
And Janusz, our great DP, said:

1070
01:14:54,199 --> 01:14:58,453
"It's a scene in a kitchen!
Why are you so happy?"

1071
01:14:58,620 --> 01:15:02,457
Because that's the movie,
and that's a stolen moment.

1072
01:15:02,624 --> 01:15:07,128
I heard that music in my head
while you were doing it.

1073
01:15:07,295 --> 01:15:11,341
And I just remember thinking
from that day on...

1074
01:15:11,549 --> 01:15:14,302
...I want to direct too,
not just write.

1075
01:15:14,469 --> 01:15:18,348
I will always think of that
when I see that scene.

1076
01:15:18,973 --> 01:15:20,850
That's what you crave.

1077
01:15:21,059 --> 01:15:25,814
Remember this shot coming up you
showed me when we were rehearsing?

1078
01:15:25,980 --> 01:15:28,942
You were going over music.
I remember this shot.

1079
01:15:29,109 --> 01:15:32,737
I remember seeing it.
Look at this.

1080
01:15:32,946 --> 01:15:36,491
You described how you were
gonna have her run.

1081
01:15:36,908 --> 01:15:39,828
-That's beautiful.
-No shoes.

1082
01:15:39,994 --> 01:15:43,123
Look at that run. So beautiful.

1083
01:15:43,331 --> 01:15:47,085
-And this shot.
-That is just awesome.

1084
01:15:47,877 --> 01:15:50,964
This is an homage
to My So-Called Life...

1085
01:15:51,172 --> 01:15:55,844
...which is one of my favourite
TV shows, where...

1086
01:15:56,010 --> 01:15:57,053
There's our band.

1087
01:15:57,220 --> 01:16:01,891
I love the feeling of it.
I later met Claire Danes and said:

1088
01:16:02,058 --> 01:16:07,522
"Did you see Jerry Maguire? There's
an homage to My So-Called Life."

1089
01:16:07,856 --> 01:16:09,858
She's like, "Yeah."

1090
01:16:11,359 --> 01:16:12,861
Is that true?

1091
01:16:13,027 --> 01:16:15,280
That's me doing a bad imitation.

1092
01:16:15,530 --> 01:16:18,366
-Thief.
-She caught it.

1093
01:16:18,575 --> 01:16:22,245
And I just loved being able
to do that.

1094
01:16:22,412 --> 01:16:24,205
That's great. "Yeah."

1095
01:16:24,414 --> 01:16:28,877
-That was magical.
-Yeah, that run down, beautiful.

1096
01:16:29,085 --> 01:16:32,547
That night was magical.
There's no other way to--

1097
01:16:32,881 --> 01:16:37,886
I'll never forget that,
never forget that day.

1098
01:16:40,096 --> 01:16:43,308
-A song for the lovers?
-No, thank you.

1099
01:16:43,475 --> 01:16:45,185
Please, no.

1100
01:16:46,269 --> 01:16:49,939
No, really, this is like
an office meeting.

1101
01:16:50,148 --> 01:16:51,232
He tips them!

1102
01:16:51,399 --> 01:16:54,861
-You knew they were coming back!
-Office meeting.

1103
01:17:00,325 --> 01:17:02,035
Before...?

1104
01:17:03,995 --> 01:17:06,331
-Jerry?
-What?

1105
01:17:07,248 --> 01:17:10,376
Let's not tell our sad stories.

1106
01:17:15,048 --> 01:17:18,551
I'll be back in just a second, okay?

1107
01:17:20,512 --> 01:17:22,180
Thank you, Renee.

1108
01:17:23,014 --> 01:17:24,766
Yeah, it was awesome.

1109
01:17:24,933 --> 01:17:27,185
My wife says that too.
"Okay, calm down."

1110
01:17:27,435 --> 01:17:30,271
"Oh, I'm an idiot. All right."

1111
01:17:30,480 --> 01:17:34,234
Same look, just quiets you down.
Awesome.

1112
01:17:37,904 --> 01:17:42,033
This is a Cameron Crowe-ism,
this moment here.

1113
01:17:42,242 --> 01:17:44,536
He lives for these moments.

1114
01:17:44,911 --> 01:17:47,372
He thinks of these moments.

1115
01:17:48,998 --> 01:17:51,960
It's the big scene
the movie hinges on.

1116
01:17:52,126 --> 01:17:55,088
"When do we get to shoot
the mariachis?"

1117
01:17:56,256 --> 01:17:59,425
You couldn't wait
to shoot the mariachis.

1118
01:17:59,801 --> 01:18:04,973
"Listen, it's great. When do we
get to the Mexican restaurant?"

1119
01:18:07,725 --> 01:18:11,062
-And this moment.
-Here's Tom, graciously...

1120
01:18:11,229 --> 01:18:14,816
...making it through another
awkward moment.

1121
01:18:15,316 --> 01:18:18,236
Graciously making it through.

1122
01:18:20,738 --> 01:18:23,491
I don't know, I dig that song.

1123
01:18:23,908 --> 01:18:26,327
Okay, here we are on the porch.

1124
01:18:28,162 --> 01:18:32,208
-Okay.
-Hey, Renee, tell us about this.

1125
01:18:33,751 --> 01:18:35,003
No!

1126
01:18:42,010 --> 01:18:43,970
Oh, that's great.

1127
01:18:51,519 --> 01:18:53,521
Thoughts, comments?

1128
01:18:53,855 --> 01:18:57,066
I felt the kiss was
a little too long.

1129
01:18:59,319 --> 01:19:02,238
But really, the kiss
is about Tidwell.

1130
01:19:02,447 --> 01:19:05,533
-That's right.
-It's the kiss.

1131
01:19:05,867 --> 01:19:10,038
-That's right.
-He's concerned with Rod's career.

1132
01:19:11,873 --> 01:19:13,374
Thank you.

1133
01:19:15,251 --> 01:19:18,963
-Okay, the music.
-Oh, and this, the lighting.

1134
01:19:19,172 --> 01:19:23,426
This floored me when we saw this
on the boat in New York.

1135
01:19:23,801 --> 01:19:25,887
The first time I ever saw it.

1136
01:19:26,054 --> 01:19:28,056
When we were shooting this...

1137
01:19:28,264 --> 01:19:32,393
...he kept saying, "This is perfect,
this is so romantic."

1138
01:19:32,727 --> 01:19:36,814
He just came in, "This is so--"
Remember that, Cameron?

1139
01:19:36,981 --> 01:19:40,401
"Just, just, just do one again.
It's working."

1140
01:19:40,568 --> 01:19:43,529
-That's great.
-And it was hysterical.

1141
01:19:43,905 --> 01:19:46,240
We couldn't depend on our dress.

1142
01:19:46,824 --> 01:19:49,911
The dress kept breaking
in the wrong places.

1143
01:19:50,078 --> 01:19:53,289
-Is this gonna--?
-And then before--

1144
01:19:53,456 --> 01:19:56,459
It's gonna work,
we'll get the straps right.

1145
01:19:56,876 --> 01:20:01,381
I remember Tom saying, "We're on
the U-train, take us there."

1146
01:20:01,589 --> 01:20:04,926
Yeah, that's right.
That's right.

1147
01:20:05,093 --> 01:20:08,930
Just take us, is it working for you?
I'm happy.

1148
01:20:09,180 --> 01:20:12,934
-Renee, you look great.
-That's awesome.

1149
01:20:13,142 --> 01:20:16,604
What you don't see
IS SO much greater.

1150
01:20:17,438 --> 01:20:19,232
You got that right.

1151
01:20:21,776 --> 01:20:25,238
Paul McCartney, solo album.

1152
01:20:29,575 --> 01:20:33,037
-This is just so good.
-Yeah.

1153
01:20:41,295 --> 01:20:43,923
I think you should not come in.

1154
01:20:45,466 --> 01:20:48,094
Or come in.

1155
01:20:52,974 --> 01:20:54,934
That's great.

1156
01:20:56,310 --> 01:20:58,229
"Same to you."

1157
01:21:01,524 --> 01:21:03,526
I live here.

1158
01:21:12,827 --> 01:21:14,996
Again, 5 in the morning.

1159
01:21:16,039 --> 01:21:18,166
This was a great night, though.

1160
01:21:18,374 --> 01:21:21,836
Because everyone had gone home,
you know?

1161
01:21:22,045 --> 01:21:24,380
-It was really basic.
-A quiet set.

1162
01:21:24,589 --> 01:21:28,634
A couple guys on camera,
couple guys running around.

1163
01:21:29,010 --> 01:21:34,390
It was very cool. Cameron's sets
are always scene-prepped.

1164
01:21:34,599 --> 01:21:40,021
Everybody's, you know, the set,
everybody's just into the movie...

1165
01:21:40,229 --> 01:21:45,193
...and help set the tone,
which comes from Cameron.

1166
01:21:45,401 --> 01:21:49,030
Scene-prepped. It's a great--

1167
01:21:49,197 --> 01:21:51,949
That kissing scene was inspired by...

1168
01:21:52,116 --> 01:21:55,620
...a scene in an old movie
starring Jean Arthur...

1169
01:21:55,953 --> 01:22:01,334
...which I thought was just a private
thing, a little private homage.

1170
01:22:01,501 --> 01:22:04,962
It was great when people
wrote about that...

1171
01:22:05,546 --> 01:22:10,426
...that we channel led Jean Arthur
in that scene. I thought:

1172
01:22:10,635 --> 01:22:12,303
"Thank you, Renee."

1173
01:22:15,056 --> 01:22:17,308
Tom was in there too, of course.

1174
01:22:19,352 --> 01:22:20,436
I didn't notice.

1175
01:22:21,938 --> 01:22:23,856
"I didn't notice."

1176
01:22:25,483 --> 01:22:28,069
As I say, you can feel Cuba.

1177
01:22:28,236 --> 01:22:31,280
Very strongly in that scene.

1178
01:22:34,867 --> 01:22:38,079
Oh, he's so good in this,
he's so funny.

1179
01:22:38,287 --> 01:22:43,126
You're sure of it. Just genius.

1180
01:22:46,546 --> 01:22:49,257
-Oh, God, he's so earnest and...
-Oh, that speech was just perfect.

1181
01:22:50,299 --> 01:22:53,219
I've read on the Net,
some jazz fans say...

1182
01:22:53,427 --> 01:22:56,013
...we're making fun of jazz fans.

1183
01:22:56,430 --> 01:22:59,433
-What?
-And it's so not the case.

1184
01:22:59,600 --> 01:23:03,521
It is celebrating the passion
of music fans.

1185
01:23:03,855 --> 01:23:08,109
In this case, a true jazz fan
of Miles and Coltrane.

1186
01:23:08,317 --> 01:23:11,904
-And also Dorothy Boyd.
-And Dorothy Boyd.

1187
01:23:12,113 --> 01:23:15,575
Dorothy a little more,
heartbroken by this...

1188
01:23:21,372 --> 01:23:24,250
He's the geek with the ear
and the lamp.

1189
01:23:24,959 --> 01:23:26,085
Yeah.

1190
01:23:31,340 --> 01:23:33,551
I love that part in the movie.

1191
01:23:47,565 --> 01:23:50,443
-Oh, terror.
-That scene was not in the script.

1192
01:23:50,610 --> 01:23:54,447
That scene was not in the script.
That was about...

1193
01:23:54,614 --> 01:23:57,533
...the chemistry of Renee and Tom.

1194
01:23:57,909 --> 01:24:02,371
-You just want that little piece.
-Let's just let them rip.

1195
01:24:02,538 --> 01:24:05,374
-And?
-Here they are.

1196
01:24:05,625 --> 01:24:07,251
And there it goes.

1197
01:24:08,669 --> 01:24:12,048
You know this is gonna
change everything.

1198
01:24:15,259 --> 01:24:16,844
Promise?

1199
01:24:22,975 --> 01:24:25,645
What is this music?

1200
01:24:26,187 --> 01:24:27,855
I love that.

1201
01:24:28,022 --> 01:24:32,860
He's just gotta hang, hang, hang.
See, that's--

1202
01:24:33,110 --> 01:24:35,821
That's the brilliance of Cameron.

1203
01:24:36,030 --> 01:24:38,366
-Not afraid--
-The pot scene?

1204
01:24:41,160 --> 01:24:46,582
That also, while that's going on,
to cut to the sister.

1205
01:24:47,583 --> 01:24:51,254
-With her to-go food.
-To allow a scene...

1206
01:24:51,504 --> 01:24:55,883
...that kind of room and not
be afraid, knowing that--

1207
01:24:56,050 --> 01:25:01,138
The intimacy and the humour,
without it being glib. I love that.

1208
01:25:03,683 --> 01:25:05,476
"This will be a great day!"

1209
01:25:07,395 --> 01:25:10,064
-That's great.
-Oh, that's great.

1210
01:25:11,065 --> 01:25:12,483
I meant the cut.

1211
01:25:19,782 --> 01:25:21,450
I did!

1212
01:25:22,451 --> 01:25:25,288
Oh, God. I mean, bad.

1213
01:25:25,496 --> 01:25:28,374
-You need a moment?
-Bad timing.

1214
01:25:28,749 --> 01:25:32,920
I need a moment to myself,
for myself and by myself.

1215
01:25:33,254 --> 01:25:37,800
Can you guys excuse me
for just a minute? Oh, God.

1216
01:25:38,342 --> 01:25:42,847
The cut to the mentor
saying "Good morning."

1217
01:25:43,097 --> 01:25:45,808
Oh, God, I have to go home.

1218
01:25:50,479 --> 01:25:51,981
How genius are you?

1219
01:25:52,231 --> 01:25:56,819
This is my favourite reaction of you,
Renee, in the whole movie...

1220
01:25:56,986 --> 01:26:00,281
...when you do the whole--
Your face is awesome.

1221
01:26:01,449 --> 01:26:04,785
-It's so funny.
- I was thinking about Rod Tidwell.

1222
01:26:06,620 --> 01:26:08,789
Why should I let this guy go...

1223
01:26:09,165 --> 01:26:10,207
It's so funny.

1224
01:26:13,919 --> 01:26:17,048
Take it easy.
I just wanted a few fun details.

1225
01:26:18,299 --> 01:26:21,802
Such a guy in the hall,
going, "Uhh!"

1226
01:26:23,137 --> 01:26:25,890
"What do I do now?"

1227
01:26:26,098 --> 01:26:28,059
You're pouring your heart out...

1228
01:26:28,267 --> 01:26:31,729
...and she's looking at you like
you're talking about cereal.

1229
01:26:31,937 --> 01:26:37,151
She's just kind of looking at you,
until this.

1230
01:26:37,693 --> 01:26:40,780
I love him for the man
he wants to be...

1231
01:26:41,030 --> 01:26:44,200
...and for the man that he almost is.

1232
01:26:46,827 --> 01:26:48,704
Oh, his face!

1233
01:26:53,959 --> 01:26:55,586
Act natural.

1234
01:26:59,173 --> 01:27:00,466
Busted.

1235
01:27:01,175 --> 01:27:03,094
Tell me he's not there.

1236
01:27:04,011 --> 01:27:06,013
The sister's in there.

1237
01:27:06,180 --> 01:27:07,723
Busted.

1238
01:27:09,392 --> 01:27:15,481
-Coffee?
-We bottom feeders prefer cereal first.

1239
01:27:15,815 --> 01:27:20,361
-Let's have Apple Jacks.
-Apple Jacks it is. Dorothy.

1240
01:27:22,947 --> 01:27:24,740
Good morning, darling.

1241
01:27:26,826 --> 01:27:31,080
Jonathan laughs like
he knows what's going on.

1242
01:27:31,831 --> 01:27:35,626
We've got a big fax today.
We need this commission.

1243
01:27:36,168 --> 01:27:38,129
No love from Apple Jacks.

1244
01:27:40,423 --> 01:27:43,968
Maybe they sent you
a couple of boxes?

1245
01:27:44,760 --> 01:27:46,137
It's an R-rated movie.

1246
01:27:46,303 --> 01:27:50,015
-There you go.
- It wasn't about the Apple Jacks.

1247
01:27:50,224 --> 01:27:52,351
-No love from Apple Jacks.
-That's cold.

1248
01:27:53,352 --> 01:27:58,357
Let's just root for a big offer
so we can move out of this room...

1249
01:27:58,607 --> 01:28:01,026
...into a real office.

1250
01:28:01,235 --> 01:28:03,946
Would you mind? Thanks a lot.

1251
01:28:06,991 --> 01:28:09,869
I thought one of the
great moments was "darling”...

1252
01:28:10,077 --> 01:28:14,415
...when Jerry calls Dorothy "darling"
in the kitchen...

1253
01:28:15,040 --> 01:28:17,001
...when he sticks up for her.

1254
01:28:20,004 --> 01:28:23,299
Then of course, the fax comes in.

1255
01:28:24,216 --> 01:28:27,136
This is the game.
I'll get back to them.

1256
01:28:27,386 --> 01:28:31,140
And say what? "Please remove
your dick from my ass"?

1257
01:28:33,058 --> 01:28:36,103
-That's great.
-Oh, she's good.

1258
01:28:36,729 --> 01:28:40,065
Regina King is awesome.

1259
01:28:42,026 --> 01:28:46,280
Just awesome. Been trying to work
with her again since this movie.

1260
01:28:46,447 --> 01:28:50,784
You know, putting something
else together. Awesome.

1261
01:28:52,077 --> 01:28:55,080
-Get me Bob Sugar on the phone.
-Marcee...

1262
01:28:57,917 --> 01:29:02,671
-You wanna leave me?
-A lot of agents say a lot of shit.

1263
01:29:02,922 --> 01:29:04,924
-You wanna leave me”?
-What do you stand for?!

1264
01:29:05,132 --> 01:29:10,304
How about integrity?
There's so much greed in the world...

1265
01:29:10,513 --> 01:29:13,474
...I don't know what to tell my son!

1266
01:29:13,682 --> 01:29:17,019
This guy isn't yelling,
"Show me the money!”

1267
01:29:20,356 --> 01:29:22,024
"Broke, broke, broke!"

1268
01:29:22,191 --> 01:29:23,776
"Dorothy, Dorothy."

1269
01:29:23,943 --> 01:29:24,944
Easy, girl.

1270
01:29:27,154 --> 01:29:31,700
-I'm not as good at insults as she is.
-That was pretty good.

1271
01:29:31,951 --> 01:29:33,827
No shit.

1272
01:29:35,120 --> 01:29:37,581
Let me show you something.

1273
01:29:37,748 --> 01:29:39,124
Yeah!

1274
01:29:39,500 --> 01:29:42,002
"Let me show you something."

1275
01:29:49,093 --> 01:29:51,512
Put that back in the box.
Let's just bury that.

1276
01:29:51,887 --> 01:29:54,306
Let's say that never happened.

1277
01:29:57,268 --> 01:30:02,523
Tell me what to do. Tell me to eat
Lima beans, I'll eat Lima beans.

1278
01:30:03,649 --> 01:30:06,569
You say this is the best,
all we can get--

1279
01:30:06,777 --> 01:30:10,155
-All we can get?
-I'm talking with my agent.

1280
01:30:10,364 --> 01:30:15,786
This is what you're gonna do. You're
gonna reject that shitty contract.

1281
01:30:16,245 --> 01:30:21,667
Play out your existing shitty contract,
and next year, you're a free agent.

1282
01:30:22,501 --> 01:30:27,840
Baby, this is us. You and me.
We determine our worth.

1283
01:30:28,132 --> 01:30:30,426
You are a strong, proud...

1284
01:30:30,634 --> 01:30:34,305
...surviving, splendid black man.

1285
01:30:36,890 --> 01:30:38,309
Marcee...

1286
01:30:39,226 --> 01:30:44,148
-How beautiful is that?
-"You're the shit."

1287
01:30:44,773 --> 01:30:46,609
Oh, baby.

1288
01:30:48,152 --> 01:30:51,238
Look at you winning
your Academy Award.

1289
01:30:55,451 --> 01:30:56,910
Rod.

1290
01:31:00,831 --> 01:31:05,753
For the handshake, I just pulled
you down, you go, "Okay."

1291
01:31:05,919 --> 01:31:08,756
-Remember?
-There it is.

1292
01:31:08,922 --> 01:31:11,842
You know? My man!

1293
01:31:14,261 --> 01:31:17,973
That's what I love
about this character...

1294
01:31:18,140 --> 01:31:22,519
...Is that he has it so together,
and every time...

1295
01:31:22,853 --> 01:31:27,441
...something gets him
off his feet, literally.

1296
01:31:27,858 --> 01:31:30,194
-I love it.
- I like these looks.

1297
01:31:30,444 --> 01:31:32,279
That's so great.

1298
01:31:34,156 --> 01:31:38,827
All Jerry wants to do is survive
and get back on his feet.

1299
01:31:38,994 --> 01:31:43,874
And he just gets bombarded by
these couples who are in love.

1300
01:31:44,041 --> 01:31:46,460
From the deaf couple on the elevator,
to Rod and Marcee...

1301
01:31:46,794 --> 01:31:51,882
...and it's, like,
"Okay, I got it.”

1302
01:31:52,132 --> 01:31:55,219
-Life is just hammering him.
-Exactly.

1303
01:31:55,427 --> 01:31:57,721
In a beautiful way.

1304
01:31:57,930 --> 01:32:00,808
Do you remember this camel?
Oh, my God!

1305
01:32:01,058 --> 01:32:03,352
Yeah, the camel chased me.

1306
01:32:03,811 --> 01:32:06,313
-He almost bit you, remember?
-Yeah, I remember!

1307
01:32:06,689 --> 01:32:08,190
That camel was no joke!

1308
01:32:08,732 --> 01:32:11,902
This was...
This is what it was like.

1309
01:32:12,486 --> 01:32:16,782
-That camel started going off.
-The camel attacked us.

1310
01:32:16,990 --> 01:32:19,702
-His trainer--
-One crew guy got stomped.

1311
01:32:20,828 --> 01:32:22,746
The trainer's trying
to keep him calm.

1312
01:32:22,955 --> 01:32:27,167
There's one shot in the movie
from when the camel attacked us.

1313
01:32:29,878 --> 01:32:31,797
I love that!

1314
01:32:32,881 --> 01:32:35,759
No, I guess there's not that shot.

1315
01:32:36,009 --> 01:32:38,345
Please join me in chapter...

1316
01:32:43,016 --> 01:32:45,477
What do you know
about single moms?

1317
01:32:45,728 --> 01:32:47,855
Oh, this is genius.

1318
01:32:49,189 --> 01:32:51,817
This is some writing right here.

1319
01:32:53,777 --> 01:32:58,073
First of all, single mothers
don't date. Watch yourself.

1320
01:32:58,282 --> 01:33:02,786
They've been to the circus.
You know what I mean?

1321
01:33:02,995 --> 01:33:06,790
They've been to the puppet show
and seen the strings.

1322
01:33:06,999 --> 01:33:09,543
-You love her?
-How do I know?

1323
01:33:09,752 --> 01:33:11,962
You know when you know.

1324
01:33:12,171 --> 01:33:16,884
I don't want her to go. I've been
hanging out at her place a lot.

1325
01:33:19,052 --> 01:33:23,056
-Mustard workout suit is--
-It's working!

1326
01:33:23,807 --> 01:33:27,102
It was like terrycloth or something.

1327
01:33:27,603 --> 01:33:32,608
She loves you. If you don't love her,
you have got to tell her.

1328
01:33:32,816 --> 01:33:34,026
This is great!

1329
01:33:34,234 --> 01:33:38,947
Women walk up to me and go, "My
boyfriend never shoplifts the pootie."

1330
01:33:39,156 --> 01:33:42,451
Every once in a while.
I'm like, "That's very nice.

1331
01:33:42,826 --> 01:33:44,536
It's very nice to hear, lady."

1332
01:33:44,912 --> 01:33:46,789
"I feel you, dog."

1333
01:33:46,955 --> 01:33:50,292
I love how he has
to say this so adamantly.

1334
01:33:50,501 --> 01:33:53,796
-"I didn't--"
- I didn't shoplift the pootie.

1335
01:33:58,926 --> 01:34:00,427
"All right.”

1336
01:34:05,265 --> 01:34:07,434
I love it!

1337
01:34:07,768 --> 01:34:12,731
We continued shooting afterwards--
"Get your ass in the car!”

1338
01:34:14,399 --> 01:34:18,946
Didn't we shoot about five different
angles of me shaking his hand?

1339
01:34:19,112 --> 01:34:20,280
We did.

1340
01:34:20,781 --> 01:34:23,784
Loved this goodbye scene.
I loved it too.

1341
01:34:23,992 --> 01:34:26,703
-How do we say goodbye?
-Look at this.

1342
01:34:27,287 --> 01:34:29,164
We had a whole...

1343
01:34:30,833 --> 01:34:33,293
Key scene with Renee and Bonnie:

1344
01:34:33,460 --> 01:34:36,088
"Let's shoot them shaking hands."

1345
01:34:36,296 --> 01:34:40,300
-"Keep them going in the back."
-"It's really funny when they..."

1346
01:34:42,427 --> 01:34:44,471
"Goodbye!"

1347
01:34:44,763 --> 01:34:46,640
All right. Goodbye.

1348
01:34:48,183 --> 01:34:50,143
"Hey, one more."

1349
01:34:50,811 --> 01:34:54,147
He said, "Don't let him go,
just keep..."

1350
01:34:55,148 --> 01:34:57,442
Here's that-- There it is.

1351
01:34:57,776 --> 01:34:59,319
"Can we shoot, please?"

1352
01:34:59,778 --> 01:35:00,946
"Okay, Jonathan."

1353
01:35:01,154 --> 01:35:02,823
Is that what he said?

1354
01:35:03,490 --> 01:35:06,493
He said, "Are we ready?
Are we gonna shoot?"

1355
01:35:11,540 --> 01:35:16,044
-I'm gonna see you this weekend.
-Go ahead and go.

1356
01:35:22,968 --> 01:35:24,928
"You jerk."

1357
01:35:25,971 --> 01:35:28,849
Sounds like a Peanuts character.

1358
01:35:29,516 --> 01:35:31,518
That's my Sonics shirt.

1359
01:35:36,023 --> 01:35:38,942
Can you do the Bridget Jones voice?

1360
01:35:39,151 --> 01:35:41,153
Absolutely not.

1361
01:35:41,320 --> 01:35:42,946
-Come on, Z.
-No way!

1362
01:35:43,155 --> 01:35:47,242
We spent a lot of time
discussing this moment.

1363
01:35:47,451 --> 01:35:49,244
Do you remember, Cameron?

1364
01:35:50,162 --> 01:35:51,872
The behaviour.

1365
01:35:53,373 --> 01:35:54,875
The glasses.

1366
01:35:55,083 --> 01:35:58,962
Yeah, we had to pick the glasses.
Very important.

1367
01:36:01,548 --> 01:36:05,218
Do a little Bridget.
Is that butterscotch?

1368
01:36:06,053 --> 01:36:09,556
-"Oh, Bridget!"
-She's got candy!

1369
01:36:10,891 --> 01:36:14,895
I was obsessed with getting
the perfect tear to be there...

1370
01:36:15,062 --> 01:36:19,107
...when Jerry tips down
Dorothy's sunglasses.

1371
01:36:19,316 --> 01:36:21,485
And she brings it.

1372
01:36:23,987 --> 01:36:27,366
It was our spiritual tip of the hat
to Billy Wilder.

1373
01:36:27,574 --> 01:36:30,577
I don't know why,
but it felt to me...

1374
01:36:31,286 --> 01:36:32,454
. like...

1375
01:36:34,331 --> 01:36:37,626
...a Billy-worthy moment if we got it.

1376
01:36:38,168 --> 01:36:42,172
-And there's the Cameron.
-Yeah, this is Cameron.

1377
01:36:44,883 --> 01:36:47,970
Turn around, walk away, turn around.

1378
01:36:48,220 --> 01:36:50,347
This one took a while.

1379
01:36:50,764 --> 01:36:54,393
This is a bizarre wedding proposal.
I'm so proud of this.

1380
01:36:54,768 --> 01:36:56,019
I love this.

1381
01:36:56,853 --> 01:36:58,313
I love this scene.

1382
01:37:05,946 --> 01:37:07,447
Will you marry me?

1383
01:37:13,620 --> 01:37:15,330
What are you thinking?

1384
01:37:16,373 --> 01:37:18,208
...like, "How am I doing?”

1385
01:37:18,375 --> 01:37:20,502
"What's going on, where am 17"

1386
01:37:20,877 --> 01:37:23,839
"Let me see how I'm doing."

1387
01:37:24,131 --> 01:37:25,549
There you are.

1388
01:37:27,426 --> 01:37:29,386
Last shot I filmed.

1389
01:37:29,970 --> 01:37:32,139
Yes, indeed, it was.

1390
01:37:34,850 --> 01:37:38,145
-That was your last shot in the movie?
-Yeah.

1391
01:37:40,230 --> 01:37:45,318
We had to get close-up footage later
because the sun was going down.

1392
01:37:45,819 --> 01:37:50,407
We were crying and they were like,
"Break for lunch, come back.

1393
01:37:51,825 --> 01:37:53,952
Can we get those tears going?"

1394
01:37:54,119 --> 01:37:57,039
"We have five minutes
and we're in overtime."

1395
01:37:58,165 --> 01:38:01,877
-This is a real moment.
-The whole crew's hungry.

1396
01:38:02,044 --> 01:38:06,048
This is a real moment because
Jonathan kept, yeah...

1397
01:38:06,381 --> 01:38:07,507
Almost.

1398
01:38:08,508 --> 01:38:11,053
He kept doing that.

1399
01:38:11,303 --> 01:38:15,265
-It was so great that we put the...
-The mariachi.

1400
01:38:15,474 --> 01:38:18,351
...priest dialog in later to match it.

1401
01:38:20,937 --> 01:38:23,523
Then Cuba couldn't wait to do this.

1402
01:38:23,940 --> 01:38:27,527
We had to pull him away.
He is a karaoke maniac.

1403
01:38:52,094 --> 01:38:56,306
I love Regina. She's like,
"That is my husband.”

1404
01:38:57,557 --> 01:39:02,145
"Let's go. Okay, he's drunk,
let's get out of here."

1405
01:39:02,479 --> 01:39:06,066
Do you remember
when we first met...

1406
01:39:06,274 --> 01:39:08,360
...and we were playing around
in the office?

1407
01:39:08,568 --> 01:39:14,074
And you put on some sunglasses
and said, "This is how I see it.

1408
01:39:14,282 --> 01:39:18,036
She has no idea it's
the greatest moment of her life...

1409
01:39:18,245 --> 01:39:22,249
...and she's walking through
her wedding day like this...

1410
01:39:22,457 --> 01:39:24,543
...and we all know the truth.

1411
01:39:24,751 --> 01:39:26,086
But she has no idea."

1412
01:39:26,294 --> 01:39:30,841
And you played the music,
and I walked around in sunglasses...

1413
01:39:31,049 --> 01:39:35,512
I'll never forget that, ever.
That was the beginning of it.

1414
01:39:35,887 --> 01:39:38,098
-She didn't know.
-She didn't.

1415
01:39:44,437 --> 01:39:47,065
Ladies and gentlemen, Bonnie Hunt.

1416
01:39:51,444 --> 01:39:53,488
Oh, look at them.

1417
01:39:53,655 --> 01:39:55,615
Nice timing, buddy.

1418
01:39:56,116 --> 01:39:59,411
I remember this.
Do you remember this shot?

1419
01:39:59,578 --> 01:40:02,038
Oh, that was the day.

1420
01:40:02,247 --> 01:40:07,460
This is another moment where
you as a director are going:

1421
01:40:07,794 --> 01:40:11,131
"Life is good."
Everybody is bringing it.

1422
01:40:11,339 --> 01:40:16,845
Cuba, realising
her private moment, right there.

1423
01:40:17,387 --> 01:40:19,514
That broke my heart.

1424
01:40:19,681 --> 01:40:21,808
Hey, that's my bro.

1425
01:40:22,434 --> 01:40:24,895
You guys really spoiled me.

1426
01:40:25,061 --> 01:40:28,690
See, now I'm gonna
release this to ESPN.

1427
01:40:30,525 --> 01:40:35,780
-You think I'm joking.
-No, it's okay. I know where you live.

1428
01:40:38,491 --> 01:40:41,411
You didn't have the talk, did you?

1429
01:40:44,206 --> 01:40:45,373
No.

1430
01:40:46,791 --> 01:40:49,961
Well, this definitely
was another way to go.

1431
01:40:51,504 --> 01:40:54,841
Hey, Dorothy, come here.

1432
01:40:55,133 --> 01:40:57,844
Tidwell brings them together.

1433
01:41:00,805 --> 01:41:02,515
Here comes the pat.

1434
01:41:05,852 --> 01:41:07,896
Look at this shot.

1435
01:41:09,522 --> 01:41:13,568
-We were just killing stunt men.
-Scott Martin.

1436
01:41:14,194 --> 01:41:17,405
-Scott Martin was on.
-There's Kelly.

1437
01:41:18,531 --> 01:41:20,909
-He's having a good game. So far.
-He is.

1438
01:41:21,326 --> 01:41:23,536
You're gonna miss him next year.

1439
01:41:23,745 --> 01:41:26,706
Loser.

1440
01:41:27,457 --> 01:41:29,334
She's venomous.

1441
01:41:37,550 --> 01:41:40,053
Catch the ball, get killed.

1442
01:41:42,973 --> 01:41:44,015
Come here.

1443
01:41:44,599 --> 01:41:47,936
-Look at Regina King do her thing.
-She's awesome.

1444
01:41:51,231 --> 01:41:55,235
And we'll let you live.
Now go kiss Daddy, quick.

1445
01:41:57,112 --> 01:42:01,616
That's one thing, whenever
I go back and see the film...

1446
01:42:02,033 --> 01:42:06,121
...it's always Regina now.
It's always Regina.

1447
01:42:06,371 --> 01:42:08,873
It's like, God. She just--

1448
01:42:09,040 --> 01:42:11,960
She represented the sports wife...

1449
01:42:12,127 --> 01:42:16,214
...holding the family together,
hoping her husband's okay.

1450
01:42:16,423 --> 01:42:21,303
And she's so perfectly seamless.
You just accept that--

1451
01:42:21,553 --> 01:42:25,307
And so were you, Renee.
Renee, easy. So were you.

1452
01:42:25,557 --> 01:42:29,102
So were you. Truly.
You don't see it because you...

1453
01:42:29,311 --> 01:42:32,314
Don't go and embarrass me
when I'm...

1454
01:42:35,775 --> 01:42:38,111
Give love to them all.

1455
01:42:43,950 --> 01:42:45,327
I love this.

1456
01:42:48,121 --> 01:42:50,290
This is the day we had the race?

1457
01:42:50,457 --> 01:42:54,919
-That's right, up those stairs.
-At 5 in the morning.

1458
01:42:58,048 --> 01:43:02,594
Take care of yourself on that field.
You're my entire client roster.

1459
01:43:02,802 --> 01:43:07,015
Don't I know this.
Now go home to your wife.

1460
01:43:07,265 --> 01:43:10,185
-What's that mean?
-What are you doing here?

1461
01:43:10,393 --> 01:43:14,898
-You could've told me on the phone.
-How about personal attention?

1462
01:43:15,106 --> 01:43:18,526
-You don't want to go home.
-What are you saying?

1463
01:43:18,777 --> 01:43:23,114
I'm just trying to talk to you.
How's your marriage?

1464
01:43:23,323 --> 01:43:26,368
The husband and wife thing,
how is that?

1465
01:43:33,792 --> 01:43:38,463
-Not everyone has what you have.
-Why did you get married?

1466
01:43:39,297 --> 01:43:43,301
-I'm just asking as a friend.
-You want an answer?

1467
01:43:43,551 --> 01:43:45,136
Loyalty.

1468
01:43:46,221 --> 01:43:47,847
She was loyal.

1469
01:43:50,517 --> 01:43:53,853
Look at you
winning your Academy Award.

1470
01:43:57,232 --> 01:43:59,067
It just...

1471
01:43:59,234 --> 01:44:01,861
I love the way Jerry--

1472
01:44:02,070 --> 01:44:07,492
Jerry believes loyalty is a
good enough reason to get married.

1473
01:44:07,867 --> 01:44:11,246
-"Grew from there."
-You're gonna laugh at me?

1474
01:44:11,454 --> 01:44:14,249
"Let me break something off
in your ass."

1475
01:44:14,457 --> 01:44:18,211
"Okay, it's that other stuff too.
You know?"

1476
01:44:18,837 --> 01:44:22,382
"Wait a minute, Rod,
let's talk for a minute."

1477
01:44:24,175 --> 01:44:26,219
And then the hit.

1478
01:44:26,428 --> 01:44:29,139
We used to laugh.
It was like, "Cuba...

1479
01:44:29,347 --> 01:44:32,475
...you're pushing Tom
out of the frame."

1480
01:44:32,892 --> 01:44:36,020
Every time, he pushed him
over the couch...

1481
01:44:36,229 --> 01:44:39,065
...pulls him through the window.

1482
01:44:39,274 --> 01:44:43,236
Cuba had no fear.
You just brought that character.

1483
01:44:43,445 --> 01:44:45,155
Beautiful.

1484
01:44:45,321 --> 01:44:48,283
You said most people
who auditioned...

1485
01:44:48,491 --> 01:44:53,204
...would see Tom and freak out.
I said, "I'll pee all over him."

1486
01:44:53,413 --> 01:44:56,916
You had your pants down.
I was like, "Hey, man."

1487
01:44:57,083 --> 01:45:01,379
I've been around certain
big stars like that, who...

1488
01:45:01,546 --> 01:45:04,257
...give off that presence.

1489
01:45:04,507 --> 01:45:08,928
But I'll give it to you, man,
you enabled me to do that.

1490
01:45:09,137 --> 01:45:13,600
You could have said,
"When they say cut, don't touch me."

1491
01:45:13,933 --> 01:45:17,395
And, "You're too hard,
can you pull back?"

1492
01:45:17,604 --> 01:45:20,148
And I'd have been, like, "Oh, shit."

1493
01:45:20,356 --> 01:45:23,276
It's like boxing with somebody...

1494
01:45:23,443 --> 01:45:26,112
...who pulls their punches. Not him.

1495
01:45:26,279 --> 01:45:31,284
That's what's fun working with
people, like you, Renee, Jay...

1496
01:45:31,451 --> 01:45:34,579
...everyone we had
was just bringing it.

1497
01:45:34,954 --> 01:45:38,124
We all felt like
we could push you around.

1498
01:45:38,291 --> 01:45:41,294
I felt like I could push
you guys too.

1499
01:45:41,544 --> 01:45:47,050
That's why you have longevity,
because you're open to people.

1500
01:45:47,300 --> 01:45:50,094
-That's the fun of it.
-It shows.

1501
01:45:50,303 --> 01:45:53,348
That's the fun of working and acting.

1502
01:45:53,515 --> 01:45:57,894
You have this writing
and this director, and you just...

1503
01:45:58,061 --> 01:46:03,483
You gotta be open to new talent,
and you are. It's awesome.

1504
01:46:05,109 --> 01:46:07,987
-The aeroplane.
-The aeroplane.

1505
01:46:08,238 --> 01:46:12,825
-The Crowe theme.
-Love that. You go. Look at you.

1506
01:46:12,992 --> 01:46:16,996
I always thought that guy
looked like David Letterman.

1507
01:46:17,205 --> 01:46:20,416
You spent a lot of time
in the editing room.

1508
01:46:20,833 --> 01:46:25,380
<i>-There's your AD.
-That was the first shot of the film.</i>

1509
01:46:25,547 --> 01:46:30,927
-Cuba in the MRI.
-You remember your A.D.? Your guy?

1510
01:46:31,094 --> 01:46:34,305
-Jerry Zeesmer.
-He was my masseuse in that.

1511
01:46:34,514 --> 01:46:39,852
We love Jerry.
Jerry comes back in this movie.

1512
01:46:40,019 --> 01:46:42,855
The aeroplanes. The aeroports.

1513
01:46:43,106 --> 01:46:47,485
I went to see this so-called
black film the other day.

1514
01:46:47,902 --> 01:46:51,155
No more salt.
Your biggest game is coming up.

1515
01:46:54,367 --> 01:46:56,619
Oh, I love her.

1516
01:46:57,203 --> 01:46:59,581
-They feed each other.
-Again.

1517
01:46:59,914 --> 01:47:04,210
-It's just hell for Jerry.
-They're doing it again.

1518
01:47:04,419 --> 01:47:07,463
-It doesn't go well.
-The kids are all over.

1519
01:47:07,839 --> 01:47:12,594
But you just die for the character
moments and the little touches.

1520
01:47:12,969 --> 01:47:16,389
The way Jerry tries to
express love for Dorothy.

1521
01:47:16,598 --> 01:47:18,516
Now it's eating at him.

1522
01:47:18,891 --> 01:47:22,562
"I could do that.
I could do that."

1523
01:47:22,937 --> 01:47:25,857
You see his face?
"I could do that."

1524
01:47:26,065 --> 01:47:29,402
-Now the baby talk.
-Isn't that nice?

1525
01:47:29,569 --> 01:47:31,571
Way to go, Jerry.

1526
01:47:32,947 --> 01:47:36,576
-Give you a little hug.
-Give you a little love.

1527
01:47:38,244 --> 01:47:40,872
-Now?
-Baby now!

1528
01:47:44,626 --> 01:47:46,586
I'm trying to catch the kids.

1529
01:47:46,919 --> 01:47:51,591
And we were laughing
because they were running around.

1530
01:47:51,966 --> 01:47:56,929
-It took me two takes to catch them.
-Cameron told them to run.

1531
01:47:57,096 --> 01:48:01,267
-I was trying hard to catch them kids.
-That was great.

1532
01:48:01,434 --> 01:48:04,604
- I like this scene.
-Me too.

1533
01:48:04,937 --> 01:48:07,940
-Lipnicki's falling asleep.
-Oh, my God!

1534
01:48:08,107 --> 01:48:13,237
Jonathan comes in and he's--
I think he's drunk in this scene.

1535
01:48:13,446 --> 01:48:16,491
-He might have been.
-He hit the bottle.

1536
01:48:16,908 --> 01:48:20,620
-He's drunk on Tom Cruise.
-Hard-working gentleman...

1537
01:48:20,995 --> 01:48:23,498
...coming to the end of his day.

1538
01:48:24,624 --> 01:48:26,668
I love this scene.

1539
01:48:28,836 --> 01:48:31,089
I thought I just did.

1540
01:48:32,006 --> 01:48:36,928
This scene was like a one-scene
homage to Carnal Knowledge...

1541
01:48:37,136 --> 01:48:40,139
...which I'm sure nobody would catch--

1542
01:48:40,390 --> 01:48:42,225
Can I come and watch TV?

1543
01:48:42,600 --> 01:48:45,228
-In just a minute.
-For a few minutes.

1544
01:48:48,856 --> 01:48:52,026
-Oh, God.
-He's probably out already.

1545
01:48:52,235 --> 01:48:55,321
-He had that baby puppy smell.
-Look at him.

1546
01:48:55,530 --> 01:48:58,324
Look at him, you can't imagine.

1547
01:48:58,533 --> 01:49:02,078
-It's the feet.
-"Can I come in and watch TV?"

1548
01:49:02,328 --> 01:49:04,205
He was exhausted.

1549
01:49:04,414 --> 01:49:08,960
- I like this close-up here.
-"He loves my kid."

1550
01:49:09,460 --> 01:49:13,172
-Can we talk about something else?
- I don't think so.

1551
01:49:13,673 --> 01:49:18,302
I gotta tell you,
I love that they're in silhouette.

1552
01:49:18,511 --> 01:49:24,016
We did it in and out of silhouette,
and it was so clearly the one.

1553
01:49:24,183 --> 01:49:27,019
Just tells a story.

1554
01:49:27,270 --> 01:49:30,440
This is Nancy Wilson's
composition, "Sandy."

1555
01:49:30,690 --> 01:49:34,694
-A Brian Wilson-esque piece.
-Isn't she something?

1556
01:49:35,027 --> 01:49:39,157
I love her. Hi, hon.

1557
01:49:42,660 --> 01:49:46,247
And I say Meryl Lee here.
That's my mother's name.

1558
01:49:46,456 --> 01:49:49,041
-Yes.
-My mama.

1559
01:49:49,208 --> 01:49:53,337
If only agents were that accessible.

1560
01:49:53,546 --> 01:49:55,715
24-7.

1561
01:49:56,466 --> 01:50:01,220
-Mine are.
-Tell Douglass I say hello.

1562
01:50:01,429 --> 01:50:03,306
Damn.

1563
01:50:04,599 --> 01:50:05,725
Damn.

1564
01:50:06,017 --> 01:50:08,394
He ain't afraid to hit below the belt.

1565
01:50:09,187 --> 01:50:11,355
That's my boy.

1566
01:50:12,064 --> 01:50:15,318
Look how cute he is. Look.

1567
01:50:15,526 --> 01:50:20,198
-Do you remember shooting this scene?
-No, not at all.

1568
01:50:20,364 --> 01:50:24,076
-Oh, that day. That was a day.
-Tell us about it.

1569
01:50:25,077 --> 01:50:28,247
Tell us about something, shit!

1570
01:50:28,414 --> 01:50:30,875
What'd you eat for breakfast?

1571
01:50:31,083 --> 01:50:33,586
Bridget, come on.

1572
01:50:35,630 --> 01:50:37,423
I'm working here, okay?
I'm working.

1573
01:50:41,552 --> 01:50:46,224
...I was in love enough
for both of us.

1574
01:50:47,475 --> 01:50:50,228
I pretended your proposal was real...

1575
01:50:50,436 --> 01:50:53,731
...when it might have been
a hypothetical.

1576
01:50:56,651 --> 01:50:58,444
He doesn't say anything.

1577
01:50:58,653 --> 01:51:03,991
"Hypothetical." Not an easy word
to just whip off and...

1578
01:51:05,868 --> 01:51:07,662
I stick.

1579
01:51:10,289 --> 01:51:13,125
-Wrong answer, buddy.
-Great face.

1580
01:51:13,459 --> 01:51:16,546
What do you want?
My soul or something?

1581
01:51:16,754 --> 01:51:22,176
-Why not? I deserve that.
-What if I'm not built that way?

1582
01:51:24,554 --> 01:51:28,516
- I think we made a mistake.
-What if it's true?

1583
01:51:30,852 --> 01:51:34,188
"Great at friendship,
bad at intimacy."

1584
01:51:34,397 --> 01:51:38,359
It's the theme of my bachelor film,
for God's sake.

1585
01:51:38,568 --> 01:51:43,364
I know, I watched it.
I sort of know it by heart.

1586
01:51:46,826 --> 01:51:51,622
- I don't like to give up.
-Please. Jerry.

1587
01:51:51,831 --> 01:51:56,878
My need to make the best of things,
and your need to be responsible...

1588
01:51:57,086 --> 01:52:01,883
If we don't say something about
it now, we could lose 10 years...

1589
01:52:02,091 --> 01:52:03,968
...being polite.

1590
01:52:05,970 --> 01:52:10,641
Let's just call this next road trip
what it really is:

1591
01:52:11,851 --> 01:52:14,186
A nice long break.

1592
01:52:22,612 --> 01:52:24,405
What about Ray?

1593
01:52:28,326 --> 01:52:30,870
Well, you'll be friends.

1594
01:52:32,204 --> 01:52:36,042
Didn't we do this scene earlier
than it was scheduled?

1595
01:52:36,208 --> 01:52:40,379
You guys sort of
had to do it last-minute.

1596
01:52:40,588 --> 01:52:43,215
And that really...

1597
01:52:43,382 --> 01:52:45,760
...really became real.

1598
01:52:46,844 --> 01:52:49,889
So this break is a breakup? That's--

1599
01:52:54,602 --> 01:52:58,230
No time to over-think it.
You just had to do it.

1600
01:52:59,273 --> 01:53:02,360
I've got this great guy.

1601
01:53:03,194 --> 01:53:06,113
And he loves my kid.

1602
01:53:08,449 --> 01:53:11,369
And he sure does like me a lot.

1603
01:53:17,875 --> 01:53:20,711
And I can't live like that.

1604
01:53:23,714 --> 01:53:26,550
It's not how I'm built.

1605
01:53:41,607 --> 01:53:45,403
I remember you doing that.
It was beautiful.

1606
01:53:45,611 --> 01:53:47,655
I remember that take.

1607
01:53:53,411 --> 01:53:55,663
I love that song.

1608
01:53:56,664 --> 01:53:58,374
Tom just bringing it.

1609
01:53:58,582 --> 01:54:03,337
We did it both ways, where the shot
moves in, and pulls out.

1610
01:54:04,213 --> 01:54:05,965
Dicky.

1611
01:54:06,132 --> 01:54:09,135
The amazing thing, well...

1612
01:54:09,343 --> 01:54:13,347
-This was a great moment.
-Oh, this is awesome.

1613
01:54:15,349 --> 01:54:18,144
Lipnicki was really asleep there.

1614
01:54:22,690 --> 01:54:27,319
This happens once in your life.
It happens once...

1615
01:54:27,528 --> 01:54:31,991
...that you get to be a part of
something like this.

1616
01:54:32,158 --> 01:54:36,996
-If you're real, real lucky.
-You got that right.

1617
01:54:37,163 --> 01:54:40,958
It's gonna happen to you
again and again, guys.

1618
01:54:42,168 --> 01:54:45,504
If somebody'd get off his butt
and get busy.

1619
01:54:45,713 --> 01:54:48,007
Oh, Bridget!

1620
01:54:50,009 --> 01:54:51,427
Bridget.

1621
01:54:51,594 --> 01:54:55,389
I love this shot with Kelly
on the escalator.

1622
01:54:55,556 --> 01:54:59,310
This is the exact--
That is The Graduate.

1623
01:54:59,852 --> 01:55:01,437
We were, I think...

1624
01:55:01,854 --> 01:55:06,442
We were the flip
of the same moving escalator...

1625
01:55:06,650 --> 01:55:09,904
...that The Graduate shot on.

1626
01:55:13,866 --> 01:55:18,120
The amazing thing
about that break-up scene is...

1627
01:55:18,370 --> 01:55:21,624
...the double-edged thing
that happened.

1628
01:55:21,957 --> 01:55:25,461
Some people
got married because of it...

1629
01:55:25,669 --> 01:55:28,881
...and some people
broke up because of it.

1630
01:55:29,090 --> 01:55:33,469
Including a woman that worked
in our editorial room.

1631
01:55:35,137 --> 01:55:37,473
Who saw it with her boyfriend.

1632
01:55:37,681 --> 01:55:41,560
I asked what they thought of it.
And she said:

1633
01:55:41,936 --> 01:55:44,313
-"We broke up!”
-Oh, my goodness.

1634
01:55:44,522 --> 01:55:48,692
And I go, "Wow,
that's really terrible."

1635
01:55:49,068 --> 01:55:53,697
And she goes, "No, it's good.
It's good!"

1636
01:55:54,073 --> 01:55:57,493
You know, and it was all about...

1637
01:55:58,410 --> 01:56:00,412
And it would go both ways.

1638
01:56:00,579 --> 01:56:03,582
That's hysterical.
"It's good, it's good."

1639
01:56:03,916 --> 01:56:06,627
Did they ever get back together?

1640
01:56:07,002 --> 01:56:09,296
I think they amicably separated--

1641
01:56:09,463 --> 01:56:11,340
They were living a lie.

1642
01:56:11,590 --> 01:56:16,303
Did they finish the picture,
or did they leave after that scene?

1643
01:56:16,512 --> 01:56:18,347
Did they see how it ended?

1644
01:56:18,597 --> 01:56:21,600
They saw it all,
and went out to dinner.

1645
01:56:21,934 --> 01:56:26,147
I'd heard this before.
People would talk afterwards...

1646
01:56:26,355 --> 01:56:29,650
And would go from being loving...

1647
01:56:30,025 --> 01:56:34,655
...to realising what they
might be lacking, or vice versa.

1648
01:56:34,989 --> 01:56:40,369
One of our first previews, a guy
proposed after the lights came on.

1649
01:56:40,703 --> 01:56:42,454
That happened a few times.

1650
01:56:42,663 --> 01:56:48,210
People say this is the movie
that she showed and he proposed.

1651
01:56:48,627 --> 01:56:52,423
-That's great.
-People left that screening at Sony...

1652
01:56:52,631 --> 01:56:56,510
...he got up and proposed
in the screening...

1653
01:56:56,719 --> 01:57:00,014
-...and they left.
- I wonder how they're doing.

1654
01:57:00,222 --> 01:57:01,974
They're divorced.

1655
01:57:02,224 --> 01:57:05,311
They came to their senses.
This guy...

1656
01:57:05,561 --> 01:57:10,649
...came up to me, it was interesting
that it was a guy...

1657
01:57:11,025 --> 01:57:14,153
-...on the set of Bridget.
-On Bridget?

1658
01:57:14,320 --> 01:57:17,156
And how did he say it exactly?

1659
01:57:19,366 --> 01:57:24,371
He said he broke up with his
girlfriend because of this film.

1660
01:57:24,622 --> 01:57:29,084
They watched the end, and when
he says, "You complete me"...

1661
01:57:29,293 --> 01:57:32,504
...he has tears in his eyes and says:

1662
01:57:32,671 --> 01:57:36,050
"That is-- It doesn't get any better.

1663
01:57:36,217 --> 01:57:40,930
That's so romantic." And he kept
going on and on about it.

1664
01:57:41,138 --> 01:57:45,184
And she said, "Is it?" And he said:

1665
01:57:46,018 --> 01:57:49,438
"Okay. Okay." And that was it.

1666
01:57:49,688 --> 01:57:54,068
And he knew he couldn't
be with her. Isn't that neat?

1667
01:57:54,276 --> 01:57:57,696
You're ruining lives
all over the world.

1668
01:57:58,113 --> 01:58:00,699
Cameron Crowe,
ladies and gentlemen.

1669
01:58:01,116 --> 01:58:05,037
-Breaking people up all over.
- I loved making this film.

1670
01:58:05,246 --> 01:58:09,416
-Let's talk about the commentators.
-Look at these guys.

1671
01:58:09,625 --> 01:58:14,380
-He was giving it up.
-Troy Aikman was still throwing.

1672
01:58:14,546 --> 01:58:17,049
You know, he's retired now.

1673
01:58:17,883 --> 01:58:20,302
But he's got a town in Texas.

1674
01:58:20,552 --> 01:58:23,889
-Does he really?
-It's Troy Aikman, Texas.

1675
01:58:24,098 --> 01:58:27,393
-Is it really?
-Right after Jerry Maguire.

1676
01:58:27,559 --> 01:58:31,647
We used footage
of a real Cardinals vs. Cowboys game.

1677
01:58:31,981 --> 01:58:36,402
We had a great time with all those
players and commentators.

1678
01:58:36,568 --> 01:58:39,488
-Look at you.
-Lining up with the guys.

1679
01:58:39,697 --> 01:58:42,992
-Look at you out there.
- I believe it.

1680
01:58:43,242 --> 01:58:45,703
Look at you. I believe you.

1681
01:58:46,078 --> 01:58:49,039
And they really
went at a brother, now.

1682
01:58:50,541 --> 01:58:55,254
-You have proof somewhere?
-Here comes the hit.

1683
01:58:58,007 --> 01:59:00,050
All the fans that we had.

1684
01:59:00,217 --> 01:59:03,512
Was it 17,000 or something
you recruited?

1685
01:59:03,887 --> 01:59:07,266
Do you remember
when we were dancing?

1686
01:59:07,516 --> 01:59:13,022
And we hung out between takes with
the players. Playing catch and stuff.

1687
01:59:13,230 --> 01:59:17,109
And Chris Mackenzie,
my trainer who built me up.

1688
01:59:17,276 --> 01:59:20,571
-He's actually a hockey player.
-Mackenzie.

1689
01:59:20,904 --> 01:59:26,118
He's out somewhere in Texas now,
playing in the Colonial League.

1690
01:59:26,285 --> 01:59:29,955
Y'all tried to call me
and invite me to that.

1691
01:59:30,122 --> 01:59:33,500
- I think so.
-You tried to call me.

1692
01:59:33,876 --> 01:59:38,505
-Actually, you called on my birthday.
-We always call Renee.

1693
01:59:38,881 --> 01:59:42,009
-Z-Dog was gone.
-You did call me.

1694
01:59:42,259 --> 01:59:46,972
-You passed the phone around.
- I think it's a miracle you're here.

1695
01:59:48,974 --> 01:59:54,271
-Because she did leave.
-Actually, this is CGI...

1696
01:59:54,480 --> 01:59:57,608
-...a miracle of technology.
-That's right.

1697
01:59:57,983 --> 02:00:02,488
It's the first
digital interview of a woman.

1698
02:00:02,821 --> 02:00:05,074
-Look at Regina.
-Go! Go!

1699
02:00:05,282 --> 02:00:07,618
-She's good.
-She's fantastic here.

1700
02:00:07,868 --> 02:00:12,748
Wasn't this the last take? You thought
you had it but did one more.

1701
02:00:12,915 --> 02:00:15,959
-Let's do one more.
-Really? Is that true?

1702
02:00:18,045 --> 02:00:22,800
Just stay calm. Keep the lines open,
I will call you back.

1703
02:00:22,966 --> 02:00:25,636
There are good doctors. Stay calm.

1704
02:00:25,844 --> 02:00:29,640
You have to tell me something.
I am freaking here.

1705
02:00:32,476 --> 02:00:35,020
-What do you think?
-She kills me.

1706
02:00:35,187 --> 02:00:39,358
You think about the athlete's family
and what they go through.

1707
02:00:42,403 --> 02:00:46,824
-Doesn't work without Rod.
- I know.

1708
02:00:47,032 --> 02:00:49,952
-Right on his neck.
-They show it so much.

1709
02:00:50,202 --> 02:00:54,540
-They show it over and over.
-It's just, you get it.

1710
02:00:54,873 --> 02:00:58,043
You get that love. You get it.
Right here.

1711
02:00:59,878 --> 02:01:00,921
Oh, God.

1712
02:01:06,552 --> 02:01:09,888
-Frank Gifford.
- I still have the football.

1713
02:01:10,055 --> 02:01:13,892
-There's Jerry.
-I'm knocked out.

1714
02:01:14,268 --> 02:01:16,019
Blink, baby! Wake up!

1715
02:01:16,228 --> 02:01:21,066
This is Jerry Zeesmer, one of
the great assistant directors.

1716
02:01:21,233 --> 02:01:25,946
-Bringing Rod to life.
-There he is, to the left.

1717
02:01:30,284 --> 02:01:34,955
Music comes in. His new life.

1718
02:01:35,539 --> 02:01:37,541
The beginning of his new life.

1719
02:01:37,916 --> 02:01:40,878
Kind of like me and this movie.

1720
02:01:41,086 --> 02:01:45,090
Seriously, after this movie
and the award...

1721
02:01:45,257 --> 02:01:48,093
I'd been acting and acting
and suddenly...

1722
02:01:48,302 --> 02:01:53,098
...I got knocked out, came to,
and got the big contract.

1723
02:01:53,265 --> 02:01:58,270
Everything came together. I had
a baby. My whole life started.

1724
02:01:58,437 --> 02:02:02,941
-Deserved, deserved.
-Everything came together.

1725
02:02:04,485 --> 02:02:06,028
He is getting up.

1726
02:02:07,196 --> 02:02:10,115
Well, my life went to crap.

1727
02:02:10,282 --> 02:02:13,285
-Listen to you.
-I was waiting for that.

1728
02:02:13,452 --> 02:02:17,623
You know it.
You know something bad's coming.

1729
02:02:17,998 --> 02:02:20,959
Oh, yeah. I love this.

1730
02:02:21,168 --> 02:02:24,546
Cameron almost killed me
with this dance.

1731
02:02:24,922 --> 02:02:29,551
"Can you do another back flip?
Okay, do everything but that."

1732
02:02:29,885 --> 02:02:34,556
Yes, ladies and gentlemen,
that is not a stunt man.

1733
02:02:34,890 --> 02:02:38,143
I just couldn't get any
enthusiasm out of you.

1734
02:02:38,393 --> 02:02:40,062
Barry Switzer.

1735
02:02:40,312 --> 02:02:44,107
Here we go,
choreographed by yours truly.

1736
02:02:44,316 --> 02:02:46,902
The fans had already seen this.

1737
02:02:47,110 --> 02:02:50,656
Cuba choreographed this whole thing.

1738
02:02:51,031 --> 02:02:56,328
No, I worked with Paula Abdul.
She showed me some stuff.

1739
02:02:56,578 --> 02:03:00,499
- I give it to her.
-We couldn't get you off the field.

1740
02:03:00,916 --> 02:03:05,170
-Yeah, I added the break dance.
-Yes, you did.

1741
02:03:06,380 --> 02:03:08,590
Okay, you know?

1742
02:03:08,966 --> 02:03:12,553
I don't think Paula
made that part up, did she?

1743
02:03:13,345 --> 02:03:16,348
-I love that.
-That answer from Regina...

1744
02:03:16,557 --> 02:03:20,519
This is pure joy, man.
Look at that, look at that.

1745
02:03:21,687 --> 02:03:25,732
I like that, he's gonna
get a flag on this.

1746
02:03:26,149 --> 02:03:30,362
-He's gonna get a flag.
-He's getting a flag on this one.

1747
02:03:30,529 --> 02:03:34,700
People said I did that dance
at the Academy Awards.

1748
02:03:35,075 --> 02:03:39,246
Well, if I did,
it's because I lost my mind again.

1749
02:03:39,454 --> 02:03:41,206
That's perfect.

1750
02:03:41,415 --> 02:03:46,378
That was beautiful when you
received the Academy Award.

1751
02:03:46,920 --> 02:03:50,632
-"Jerry Maguire."
- I almost choked on my hamburger...

1752
02:03:51,008 --> 02:03:52,968
...screaming and clapping for you.

1753
02:03:53,176 --> 02:03:56,221
-"You're gonna pay."
-You're gonna pay.

1754
02:03:57,055 --> 02:04:00,350
Show him the money! You know?!

1755
02:04:00,559 --> 02:04:03,562
Do you remember
when we were doing that?

1756
02:04:05,063 --> 02:04:07,316
-That's awesome.
-Oh, God, man.

1757
02:04:07,566 --> 02:04:12,446
Cuba, if you didn't play this
character with such joy throughout...

1758
02:04:12,654 --> 02:04:14,489
...we'd be dead.

1759
02:04:14,698 --> 02:04:19,578
It'd just be an angry guy.
Which would be great...

1760
02:04:19,911 --> 02:04:21,913
...but it wouldn't be Tidwell.

1761
02:04:22,080 --> 02:04:26,460
You know where the dance
comes from. It's part of you.

1762
02:04:26,668 --> 02:04:30,589
-And Tom and I doing this moment.
-Look at this.

1763
02:04:31,006 --> 02:04:35,344
-It was awesome.
-Talk about your great screen couples.

1764
02:04:35,594 --> 02:04:40,599
- I ain't doing no kissing though.
-No, baby, no way. Uh-uh.

1765
02:04:40,932 --> 02:04:43,143
-That was awesome, dude.
-New season, the bathroom.

1766
02:04:43,310 --> 02:04:46,521
Now who's this guy
in the background?

1767
02:04:46,730 --> 02:04:48,732
- I love this.
- I love this.

1768
02:04:49,107 --> 02:04:51,943
And he goes, let's go for it.

1769
02:04:53,278 --> 02:04:57,616
-Go, Jay Mohr.
-This is a real football player too.

1770
02:04:57,949 --> 02:04:59,701
He's awesome.

1771
02:05:01,995 --> 02:05:03,580
Dorothy?

1772
02:05:07,459 --> 02:05:08,794
What's this guy saying behind you?

1773
02:05:09,044 --> 02:05:11,463
He's like, "Rod, come on, man."

1774
02:05:12,214 --> 02:05:14,049
"Rod! Rod!"

1775
02:05:14,257 --> 02:05:19,221
I have to say this. We were in
Arizona, which was two hours ahead...

1776
02:05:19,471 --> 02:05:23,600
...it was like 3 a.m.,
or however it worked in L.A...

1777
02:05:23,975 --> 02:05:28,647
...Regina was asleep, you called
and got her on her phone...

1778
02:05:28,980 --> 02:05:33,985
...and after the first take--
She's just giving me everything.

1779
02:05:34,152 --> 02:05:38,240
And after the take
I asked her if she was asleep.

1780
02:05:38,490 --> 02:05:44,287
She said, "Yeah, but that's okay."
She was asleep and woke up for that.

1781
02:05:44,496 --> 02:05:47,040
- I love you.
-She's the best.

1782
02:05:47,249 --> 02:05:50,627
She was asleep
and she was bringing it.

1783
02:05:51,002 --> 02:05:55,006
-Thank you, Janusz Kaminski.
-Yeah, thank you, Janusz.

1784
02:05:59,052 --> 02:06:03,348
This is my mom, who is completely
unaware of the camera.

1785
02:06:08,061 --> 02:06:12,733
This is my mom.
She's a counsellor, still, and...

1786
02:06:13,066 --> 02:06:16,153
-Here's my line.
-She's a great lady.

1787
02:06:16,361 --> 02:06:17,571
This is great.

1788
02:06:26,079 --> 02:06:29,040
She's, like, bringing it on.

1789
02:06:29,249 --> 02:06:32,502
I gotta thank Bets
for that jacket, also.

1790
02:06:32,711 --> 02:06:36,381
My mom says,
"Put me more in your movies."

1791
02:06:36,548 --> 02:06:41,720
I say, "You have Tom outside,
staring at you through the window...

1792
02:06:42,095 --> 02:06:45,974
...and it's a love story with Renee.
What do you want?"

1793
02:06:48,518 --> 02:06:52,814
Maybe you're all correct.
Men are the enemy.

1794
02:06:53,023 --> 02:06:56,610
No, they're not the enemy.

1795
02:06:56,860 --> 02:07:00,197
But I still love the enemy.

1796
02:07:08,038 --> 02:07:09,998
This is classic.

1797
02:07:14,085 --> 02:07:16,963
Hello. Hello.

1798
02:07:17,839 --> 02:07:20,217
I'm looking for my wife.

1799
02:07:32,729 --> 02:07:33,897
Wait.

1800
02:07:36,942 --> 02:07:39,861
-I love that--
-"Who is this guy?"

1801
02:07:43,281 --> 02:07:44,449
Lorraina.

1802
02:07:49,871 --> 02:07:54,793
I'm not letting you get rid of me.
How about that?

1803
02:07:58,004 --> 02:07:59,923
Knight in shining arm our.

1804
02:08:00,382 --> 02:08:04,553
This used to be my speciality.
I was good in a living room.

1805
02:08:04,761 --> 02:08:06,388
I'd do it alone.

1806
02:08:07,180 --> 02:08:09,182
And now, I just...

1807
02:08:15,272 --> 02:08:16,690
I don't know.

1808
02:08:22,195 --> 02:08:23,989
But tonight...

1809
02:08:24,906 --> 02:08:30,287
...our little project, our company
had a very big night.

1810
02:08:30,787 --> 02:08:35,041
A very, very big night.

1811
02:08:38,003 --> 02:08:40,046
But it wasn't complete.

1812
02:08:42,549 --> 02:08:48,179
It wasn't nearly close to being
in the same vicinity as complete...

1813
02:08:48,638 --> 02:08:51,308
...because I couldn't
share it with you.

1814
02:08:52,642 --> 02:08:54,686
I couldn't hear your voice...

1815
02:08:57,022 --> 02:08:59,649
...or laugh about it with you.

1816
02:09:02,027 --> 02:09:05,196
I missed my-- I missed my wife.

1817
02:09:21,546 --> 02:09:26,760
We live in a cynical world.
A cynical world.

1818
02:09:27,260 --> 02:09:31,973
And we work in a business
of tough competitors.

1819
02:09:41,650 --> 02:09:43,443
I love you.

1820
02:09:43,693 --> 02:09:45,111
You...

1821
02:09:46,863 --> 02:09:48,657
...complete me.

1822
02:09:50,075 --> 02:09:52,160
-And I just--
-Shut up.

1823
02:09:53,536 --> 02:09:55,121
Just shut up.

1824
02:09:55,872 --> 02:09:58,041
You had me at "hello."

1825
02:09:59,250 --> 02:10:01,586
You had me at "hello."

1826
02:10:06,132 --> 02:10:07,968
Thanks, you guys.

1827
02:10:12,389 --> 02:10:16,101
I was never sure about that speech.
I thought...

1828
02:10:17,102 --> 02:10:21,940
...you know, is it too much,
is it too...

1829
02:10:22,524 --> 02:10:25,110
...heart-in-hand, you know?

1830
02:10:25,318 --> 02:10:30,115
Tom was always "Let me do it."

1831
02:10:31,241 --> 02:10:35,495
-I remember him doing it.
-"Take it away, I'll kill you."

1832
02:10:35,870 --> 02:10:38,957
Immediately you felt that.

1833
02:10:39,165 --> 02:10:43,878
I remember doing it and looking
at people, and they were just...

1834
02:10:44,129 --> 02:10:46,339
-Destroyed.
-Destroyed.

1835
02:10:46,548 --> 02:10:49,968
There were three women
by the monitor.

1836
02:10:50,135 --> 02:10:53,638
I turned when you said,
"We live in a cynical world."

1837
02:10:54,014 --> 02:10:58,977
Which was an important thing
that we had talked about...

1838
02:10:59,144 --> 02:11:03,440
I said, "How's this working?"
They'd be, like--

1839
02:11:05,984 --> 02:11:09,279
And it was you
connecting to it personally.

1840
02:11:09,446 --> 02:11:13,908
It was more than just words.
It was a feeling, and then...

1841
02:11:17,579 --> 02:11:20,457
And then we get this gift from Cuba.

1842
02:11:22,500 --> 02:11:25,170
I always loved that speech.

1843
02:11:26,046 --> 02:11:31,176
On this one, you told me to hug him
and kiss him. Do you remember?

1844
02:11:31,342 --> 02:11:35,430
-Oh, yeah, that's right.
-"Just hug him and kiss him."

1845
02:11:35,638 --> 02:11:40,477
Isn't that Leigh Steinberg,
who always says he's Jerry Maguire?

1846
02:11:40,643 --> 02:11:43,021
There he is, in the maroon tie!

1847
02:11:43,188 --> 02:11:46,483
He took the picture of me
and Cuba on the set.

1848
02:11:47,567 --> 02:11:50,779
You remember Troy
from the Super Bowl?

1849
02:11:50,945 --> 02:11:51,988
We met in '93.

1850
02:11:52,155 --> 02:11:55,492
-That's right. I enjoyed your memo.
-Thank you.

1851
02:11:55,825 --> 02:12:00,830
-A little slow but you come around.
-We're out of time.

1852
02:12:01,039 --> 02:12:02,999
I'm forgetting somebody.

1853
02:12:06,419 --> 02:12:08,171
Look at this, I love this.

1854
02:12:15,178 --> 02:12:18,431
-Yeah, baby.
-That's Jerry Maguire.

1855
02:12:18,598 --> 02:12:21,518
-Look, there it is.
-Kisses.

1856
02:12:23,645 --> 02:12:28,233
-Awesome, dude. Awesome.
-Brother.

1857
02:12:28,441 --> 02:12:31,111
-Awesome!
-Remember shooting this?

1858
02:12:31,319 --> 02:12:33,863
I'll never forget it.

1859
02:12:34,072 --> 02:12:37,951
I was like,
"this can't be almost over."

1860
02:12:38,118 --> 02:12:41,454
-Famke came.
-Yeah, my friend. She did.

1861
02:12:42,122 --> 02:12:43,414
She did.

1862
02:12:47,585 --> 02:12:48,920
Good throw, man.

1863
02:12:51,965 --> 02:12:53,633
Did you see?

1864
02:12:54,300 --> 02:12:56,970
Oh, no. Let's go.

1865
02:12:57,637 --> 02:13:02,600
This is an alternate version
of Dylan's "Shelter from the Storm."

1866
02:13:02,892 --> 02:13:05,478
He dug into the vaults to give us.

1867
02:13:05,854 --> 02:13:07,313
Really?

1868
02:13:07,522 --> 02:13:12,944
And there's a funny thing here.
They're going off into the sunset.

1869
02:13:13,111 --> 02:13:18,032
But the beautiful layer
that you guys gave us was:

1870
02:13:18,199 --> 02:13:23,413
You don't know what'll happen.
Tidwell could be out with one injury.

1871
02:13:23,580 --> 02:13:26,958
He may still not be in love enough.

1872
02:13:27,208 --> 02:13:28,543
I love Dicky Fox here.

1873
02:13:28,918 --> 02:13:33,965
But Dicky gives it to you.

1874
02:13:34,215 --> 02:13:35,842
That's good.

1875
02:13:36,342 --> 02:13:38,136
You did that, that's good.

1876
02:13:38,344 --> 02:13:40,346
"My kind of success."

1877
02:13:40,847 --> 02:13:44,934
Cameron Crowe,
thank you for the experience.

1878
02:13:45,143 --> 02:13:48,813
-Thank you, dude!
-Thank you for the experience.

1879
02:13:49,063 --> 02:13:50,273
You guys, that was--

1880
02:13:50,481 --> 02:13:53,151
Love you, man.

1881
02:13:53,359 --> 02:13:54,986
I love you guys.

1882
02:13:55,153 --> 02:13:58,656
I've been asked to do this,
I've always said no.

1883
02:13:58,990 --> 02:14:04,037
I thought, I'll do it for you.
I'll sit down with Renee and Cuba.

1884
02:14:04,204 --> 02:14:07,498
But I really enjoyed doing it.

1885
02:14:07,665 --> 02:14:10,126
Also, I loved making this movie.

1886
02:14:10,335 --> 02:14:14,923
I loved working with you,
Renee and Cuba. It was fun.

1887
02:14:15,131 --> 02:14:19,260
-A beautiful experience.
-Even to the European tour.

1888
02:14:19,469 --> 02:14:22,305
You are a great filmmaker.

1889
02:14:22,472 --> 02:14:25,975
Cameron Crowe,
you are a great filmmaker.

1890
02:14:26,184 --> 02:14:28,478
Actors worship you.

1891
02:14:28,686 --> 02:14:30,355
I gotta say...

1892
02:14:30,605 --> 02:14:34,359
...we got to be in one
of the greatest movies ever.

1893
02:14:34,525 --> 02:14:36,319
Love this picture.

1894
02:14:36,527 --> 02:14:41,157
-And Billy Wilder saw it and dug it.
- I know.

1895
02:14:41,366 --> 02:14:42,951
-I remember.
-To Billy!

1896
02:14:43,159 --> 02:14:47,247
I remember that day. "He's on
his way." I was sweating.

1897
02:14:47,497 --> 02:14:51,960
"He's on his way.
He's gonna see the movie."

1898
02:14:52,126 --> 02:14:55,880
Then there was that gap:
"He's watching the movie."

1899
02:14:56,089 --> 02:15:01,427
I was saying, "Come on, I was down
by the phone, three hours later.”

1900
02:15:01,844 --> 02:15:05,223
It was the whole reason
for doing it, wasn't it?

1901
02:15:05,473 --> 02:15:09,227
The whole idea was
to just tell a story.

1902
02:15:09,435 --> 02:15:12,855
Tell a story the way Wilder
told a story...

1903
02:15:13,064 --> 02:15:15,942
...where you could turn the TV
on at night.

1904
02:15:16,150 --> 02:15:20,071
You meet these people that
take you on a ride for two hours.

1905
02:15:20,238 --> 02:15:23,908
-They leave your life, but never really.
-But it's Crowe.

1906
02:15:24,075 --> 02:15:25,159
It's Crowe.

1907
02:15:25,368 --> 02:15:29,455
Tip your hat to Wilder,
but it is Crowe.

1908
02:15:29,831 --> 02:15:31,916
He had his own signature.

1909
02:15:32,083 --> 02:15:37,422
If you look at this movie, it really
defies traditional structure.

1910
02:15:37,588 --> 02:15:42,010
You look at that and you go,
"That is a Crowe movie."

1911
02:15:42,260 --> 02:15:45,388
-That's Crowe.
-Is that too weird?

1912
02:15:45,555 --> 02:15:48,558
You know, James L. Brooks
is a huge...

1913
02:15:48,891 --> 02:15:53,771
...part of the DNA of this.
We spent years on this script.

1914
02:15:53,938 --> 02:15:56,149
Jim would always say:

1915
02:15:56,357 --> 02:16:01,279
"I want this to be something that
came from your deepest part.

1916
02:16:01,487 --> 02:16:05,366
And we can't stop until
it's exactly that."

1917
02:16:05,575 --> 02:16:09,954
And he was our greatest partner
on this...

1918
02:16:10,121 --> 02:16:13,583
...who's not here,
but we send our props to him.

1919
02:16:13,916 --> 02:16:16,210
-Props to Jim.
-Yes, props to Jim.

1920
02:16:16,419 --> 02:16:18,004
James L. Brooks.

1921
02:16:18,254 --> 02:16:23,384
I hear him, watching the movie,
I hear his voice so much, saying:

1922
02:16:23,593 --> 02:16:27,638
"Buddy, you're gonna get
these actors out there.

1923
02:16:27,972 --> 02:16:33,144
You'll have a great time. All I want
is to protect the experience.”

1924
02:16:33,311 --> 02:16:35,521
He did, he and Richard Sakai...

1925
02:16:35,772 --> 02:16:40,943
...were great producers that allowed
us the cocoon to work in.

1926
02:16:41,152 --> 02:16:43,863
So I just wanna say that.

1927
02:16:44,072 --> 02:16:47,784
But within the cocoon it was
quite an experience.

1928
02:16:47,992 --> 02:16:50,328
And I still...

1929
02:16:50,745 --> 02:16:55,166
I can feel it and smell it
every time I see the movie.

1930
02:16:55,375 --> 02:16:57,001
Thanks.

1931
02:16:57,168 --> 02:16:58,753
Cool.

1932
02:16:58,961 --> 02:17:01,172
And here's Nancy's theme song.

1933
02:17:01,339 --> 02:17:03,383
Yeah. Nice way to go out.

1934
02:17:03,549 --> 02:17:06,844
You know, she ain't bad, huh?

1935
02:17:07,011 --> 02:17:09,806
-She ain't bad.
-Thanks.

1936
02:17:09,972 --> 02:17:11,474
We love you, Nance!

1937
02:17:11,849 --> 02:17:13,476
Come over here!

1938
02:17:13,851 --> 02:17:16,854
-We love Nance.
-We love her.

1939
02:17:17,105 --> 02:17:19,023
Scott Martin, Lisa Steward.

1940
02:17:19,190 --> 02:17:23,194
Yeah, can't forget those guys.
Speaking of cocoons.

1941
02:17:23,403 --> 02:17:25,363
-Michael Doven.
-Doven!

1942
02:17:25,530 --> 02:17:27,031
The Dovenator.

1943
02:17:27,281 --> 02:17:31,202
-Shawn, Derrick.
-Shawn and Derrick.

1944
02:17:31,369 --> 02:17:32,829
The boys.

1945
02:17:33,037 --> 02:17:34,580
LeAnne.

1946
02:17:36,207 --> 02:17:38,418
Pushy John Caravino.

1947
02:17:38,793 --> 02:17:42,046
-Pat Kingsley.
-Pat Kingsley.

1948
02:17:42,255 --> 02:17:44,298
-All over it.
-That's right.

1949
02:17:44,507 --> 02:17:47,885
And all of these musicians.
Look at this music.

1950
02:17:48,094 --> 02:17:49,804
You're good at that.

1951
02:17:49,971 --> 02:17:53,015
You kind of make me mad, in fact.

1952
02:17:53,182 --> 02:17:57,103
Come on, give us a little Bridget
on the credits.

1953
02:17:57,270 --> 02:18:01,566
It's not happening.
No, forget about it.

1954
02:18:01,941 --> 02:18:03,943
Come on, Renee.

1955
02:18:04,152 --> 02:18:05,903
Bust out something.

1956
02:18:06,070 --> 02:18:09,782
Just give us something.
You won't tell us what's going on.

1957
02:18:10,032 --> 02:18:11,742
I'm on vacation.

1958
02:18:11,909 --> 02:18:13,077
And we're not.

1959
02:18:13,286 --> 02:18:16,080
Break out just a sentence of Bridget.

1960
02:18:16,289 --> 02:18:20,042
Give us a sentence.
Look, it's going to Dolby.

1961
02:18:20,251 --> 02:18:22,462
-Another minute.
-One on Dolby.

1962
02:18:22,795 --> 02:18:24,422
Come on, you guys.

1963
02:18:26,466 --> 02:18:29,302
You ain't behind the camera.
Ain't acting. Sorry.

1964
02:18:29,594 --> 02:18:33,806
The Bridget Jones DVD
she'll do it for like two and a half hours.

1965
02:18:33,973 --> 02:18:35,391
Yeah, exactly.

